by the latter are expressly noted three copies of the new translation of the Bible (the Vulgate) and one of the old (the Itala). Bede, who in his commentar-ies is constantly comparing the two translations together ¹, may often have used these very copies. One of the three Vulgates was taken by Ceolfrid with him on his departure as a present to the Pope 3 and this has been identified beyond a doubt with the famous Codex Amiatinus of the Vulgate 2. There is moreover abundant evidence of the existence of a system of lending MSS. from one monastery to another for the purpose of transcription and comparison 3. The latter process has left its mark on many MSS. which have come down to us. Thus two of the oldest MSS. of Bede’s Ecclesiastical History have evidently been compared to- gether, and the readings of one transferred to the other ⁴.
